SIMPLE: puncture
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puncture
<hw>Punc"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>punctura</ets>, fr. <ets>pungere</ets>, <ets>punctum</ets>, to
prick. See <er>Pungent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
puncturing; perforating with something pointed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small hole made by a point; a slight wound, bite,
or sting; <as>as, the <ex>puncture</ex> of a nail, needle, or
pin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lion may perish by the <qex>puncture</qex> of an asp.</q>
<rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puncture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Puncture
<hw>Punc"ture</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Punctured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Puncturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To pierce with a small,
pointed instrument, or the like; to prick; to make a puncture in;
<as>as, to <ex>puncture</ex> the skin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punctured</ent>⟦br⟧
